I would suggest asking your own questions during the "Q&A" phase of your interview. The questions you are asked aren't particularly difficult and you won't glean much information about the position from them. Of course if you are bringing your own clients with you, don't worry about asking questions.

job_title: Marketing Associate/Account Executive/Management Trainee was asked...
interview_question: This place is a SCAM. I applied for the 'marketing associate role,' and got a call saying I had been shortlisted for an interview. I asked the recruiter which role I was being considered for, and she told me I was being considered for the ' account executive' role. I was confused at this point since I didn't even apply to this role. I told the recruiter I wasn't interested in a sales role, I wanted to do marketing, and she assured me it would be 80 percent marketing. I went in for an interview, and the office was almost bare empty and looked like they just moved in. After asking several questions, the man whom I interviewed with told me I was being considered for the 'Management Trainee' role. This was now the third different role they told me I was being considered for, NONE of which I even applied for. I asked him what the salary would be and he told me that it was "competitive," and I would learn more in the second interview. For the second interview, the woman interviewing explained thier 'training process.' She pointed to a flow chart, titled 'Executive Training Program'-- where the jobs listed ' account executive, account manager, junior executive, and senior executive,' with corresponding lengths for each role. She told me the first 2 (account executive, account manager) take up to 6 months before you can advance. I asked her about compensation for each of those two roles, to which she responded 400- 500 a month. I asked her if that was on top of commission-- and she responded that they ONLY do commission. NO BASE SALARY!!!! I was shocked because at this point, I had not only been lured into an office in which a job title I applied for didn't exist, they are totally untransparent about their roles AND their "competitive salary. "

You are given a business scenario and asked 4-5 questions (calculate the profite made over the first year of openning a new shop; what would you advise if you can only make a new website or a new shop (here you calculate profitability again (easy, just like profit= revenue - costs), and the two other questions are verbal, see if you can be creative).

The face-to-face interview questions are pretty standard. They are clear with you that they want to assess your drive, intellect, executive presence and sales skills. Overall, they are looking for a successful candidate to have the 'right traits' for Gartner - positivity, enthusiasm, strong motivation and drive to succeed, structured approach to setting and (over)achieving goals. The panel interview is looking for more of the same, with a more intensive focus on your ability to uncover a prospect's real pain points during a role-play first meeting with a CIO and then a closer look at your ability to sell yourself, when you get to formally present to the room why you and Gartner are a match made in heaven.

interview_question: All questions were behavioral interview questions.

If you are under quota with amount of calls what would you do?
I want you to sell me a car.

How would you penetrate an account? (email, in person, phone, vm but failed to mention social media. The sales manager disqualified me because I failed to mention this part; which I assumed it was the norm. What is your 30-60-90 business plan? What do you know about the company? Why the company? Why did you leave your other jobs? What guarantees do we have that you won't be leaving us? What do you know about the cloud?

Why do you want to work in sales? What do you think will be the most challenging part of sales? How would you approach a situation where you did not make any sales at all?
